@section Devices
@cindex Devices
@cindex RPC
@cindex RAM Pointer Count

A device is --- like a library (see @ref{Libraries}) --- a collection
of functions/procedures, which have to do certain jobs.

E.g. the @file{trackdisk.device} includes functions for the floppy disk
handling.


@subheading Column items

@table @samp
@item Address
Address of the device structure

@item ln_Name
Name of a device

@item ln_Pri
Priority of a device

@item OpenC
This element shows how often the device was opened.

@item RPC
@samp{RPC} means @samp{RAM Pointer Count} and shows how many jump
addresses of the device point into RAM.  In this way many programs ---
like the @code{setpatch} command from Commodore --- patch the system.

Many viruses patch the system in this way too, but don't panic now.
If you check your system in regular intervals with a current virus
killer, it should be out of danger.

If the whole program code of the device is located in RAM, you will
find a dash (minus sign) here, because in this case it's unimportant
how many jump addresses point into RAM.

@item ln_Type
Type of this structure (usually @samp{device})
@end table


@subheading Actions

@table @samp
@item Update
If you select this gadget, the list of devices will be updated.

@item Print
This function allows you to send the list of @samp{Devices} to
printer or a selected file.

@item Remove
The selected device will be removed with this function provided that no
program uses this device anymore and the @samp{OpenC} is zero.

@item Priority
Herewith the priority of the device can be changed.  A little window
will be opened, that asks you for a new priority.  Through the new
priority it can happen that the device gets a new place in the device
list.

@item More
Another window will be opened and you will see more informations about
the selected device.

You will have the same effect, if you doubleclick an element of the
device list.

@item Functions
All device function offsets and addresses are shown up in a subwindow.
If an appropriate @file{.fd} file exists and an @file{FD:} assign points
to its directory, then you will also see the function names.

@item Exit
The @samp{Devices} window will be closed.
@end table
