@section InputHandlers
@cindex InputHandlers
@cindex Input events

Input handlers take care of all user input arriving in system
(pressed keys, mouseclicks, inserted disks, etc.). They stand one
behind the other like on a production line and analyze the user input.
The input handler with the highest priority gets the `events' first
and if it doesn't know how to react on these `events', the second input
handler gets them, and so on.

Usually the system input handler has a priority of 50.  Every input
handler, that wants to get the user input before the system, must have
a higher priority.


@subheading Column items

@table @samp
@item ln_Name
Name of the input handler

@item ln_Pri
Its priority

@item is_Data
This address points to some data needed by the input handler.

@item is_Code
The program code starts here.  If the code is located in RAM, the
address is of different color.  Otherwise you can find the code in
ROM.  Some viruses install an input handler in system.  In this case
the @samp{is_Code} address points into RAM, but many other programs uses
input handlers, too.  Don't panic!
@end table


@subheading Actions

@table @samp
@item Update
The list of input handlers will be updated when you select this gadget.

@item Print
This function allows you to send the list of @samp{InputHandlers} to
printer or a selected file.

@item Remove
Removes an input handler from system.

@item Priority
Changes the priority of an input handler.

@item Exit
The window will be closed.
@end table

