@section Tasks
@cindex Tasks
@cindex Processes

In this window you find a list of all tasks and processes being in
system. Each program you start will be executed as a task or process.


@subheading Column items

@table @samp
@item ln_Name
Name of the task/process

@item ln_Type
Type of the structure (@samp{task} or @samp{process})

@item ln_Pri
Priority of the task/process

@item NUM
If a non detaching program was started from shell, you will find here
the number of the process. Programs you started from Workbench have a
dash here.

@item State
Here you see the state of the task or process. You will find
Scout's own process on the top of the list with a @samp{run} at
this place, because this process is always running when it gets the
task list.

@samp{ready} means the task wants to work, but it's interrupted by
the execution of another task.

A task that is waiting for a certain signal is in the state
@samp{wait}. In this case it doesn't need processing time.

@item SigWait
Signalmask the task is waiting for.
@end table


@subheading Actions

@table @samp
@item Print
This function allows you to send the list of @samp{Tasks} to
printer or a selected file.

@item Freeze
With this function you freeze the selected task. It can still be found
in the list of tasks, but it gets no processing time from system.

@quotation
@strong{Warning:}
If you try to freeze tasks essential to the system like
`input.device', you should have saved all important data, cause a
RESET is the only way out!
@end quotation

@item Activate
A frozen task can be activated here.

@item CPU
Here you will find a text field and a cycle gadget. This text field
displays --- dependent on the state of the cycle gadget --- the CPU
load in percent.

For the cycle gadget you can choose between three states:
@table @samp
@item off
In this case the CPU load won't be displayed. If you select another
state, @code{Scout} will patch some system functions to calculate the
CPU load of all tasks.

@item full
If you select this state, @code{Scout} sets the real cpu load to 100%.
That means the total of the CPU loads of all tasks and processes will
be 100%. Therefore nothing will be displayed in the text field.

@item in %
@code{Scout} starts a task named @samp{ Scout's cheat task } to
calculate the real CPU load and it will be displayed in the text
field.
@end table

@item Secs
This string gadget allows you to set the intervall time for updating
of the CPU load display.

@item Update
The list will be updated.

@item Remove
A task will be removed from the list.  You should prefer the freeze
function, if you perhaps need this task again.

See also @samp{Break}!

@item Signal
If you select a signal mask, it will be send to the task.

@item Break
A signal mask that includes the signals CTRL-C and CTRL-D will be
send to the task you selected.  Many tasks and processes end, if
they receive these signals.

@item Priority
The priority of a task can be changed with this function.

@item More
Selecting this gadget will open another window that displays more
informations about the task or the process.

@item Exit
The window will be closed.
@end table

