@section Scout and AmiTCP

This section will show you what you have to do for using @code{Scout}
as a TCP/IP service through @code{AmiTCP}. Nearly all functions of
@code{Scout} can also be used via @code{AmiTCP}.

Now some knowledge will be assumed. If you don't know, what kind of
program @code{AmiTCP} represents, you should read @code{AmiTCP's} user's
manual before. (See also @ref{AmiTCP}.)

If you have installed @code{AmiTCP}, you can use @code{Scout} as client
and server. Except the installed programs of @code{AmiTCP} you don't need
another program for using @code{Scout} on networks.

If you want to make your computer available for other systems on the
network, you have to do following two steps:

@enumerate
@item Add the line @samp{scout 6543/tcp} to file @file{AmiTCP:db/services}.

@item Now please add the line @samp{scout stream tcp nowait root dh0:scout}
to file @file{AmiTCP:db/inetd.conf}. Make sure that the path at the
end of this line is the right path for @code{scout}.
@end enumerate

That's it! If you start @code{AmiTCP} now, your computer is available
for other systems through using the options @samp{HOST}, @samp{USER}
and @samp{PASSWORD}.

@quotation
@noindent @strong{Example:} If I want perform some actions on some system
structures of my own system for example, I have to start @code{Scout}
through something like:

@format
1> scout HOST crash.north.de USER atte PASSWORD secret
@end format
@end quotation

If you leave out option @samp{PASSWORD}, you will be asked for the
correct password through the @samp{password:} prompt. In this case
nobody can see your password, because it won't be displayed in shell.

If you don't use option @samp{USER}, @code{AmiTCP} takes the username
that is actually available in system.

The usage of @code{AmiTCP} doesn't provide the installation of
@code{MUI}. All of @code{Scout's} shell commands (see also @ref{Commands})
can be used via network through @code{AmiTCP}.

@quotation
@noindent @strong{Example:} If I want to get the task list of my
system, I have to use something like:

@format
1> scout HOST crash.north.de USER atte PASSWORD secret Tasks
@end format
@end quotation

You and all other users must always identify themselves through
their usernames (option @samp{USER}) and their passwords
(option @samp{PASSWORD}).
It's also possible to allow or deny certain systems the usage of
some services through the file @file{AmiTCP:db/inet.access}. See also
the user's manual of @code{AmiTCP}.

If you want to get more informations about the implemented options and
commands, you should also see @ref{Options} and @ref{Commands}.

@strong{NOTE:} Please take care that the remote system runs the latest
Scout version as well, to avoid incompatibilities.

