@chapter Options
@cindex Options
@cindex Tool Types
@cindex Command Line Options

There are some options for @code{Scout} which you can use, when you
start the program.  The following options are available from shell and
as tool types from Workbench.

@table @samp
@item ICONIFIED
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{ICONIFIED}
@end format

If this option is activ, @code{Scout} starts iconified.

@item PORTNAME
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{PORTNAME}=@var{portname}
@end format

The name of Scout's ARexx port can be changed into @var{portname}.
Without this option the ARexx port is called `SCOUT.X'. The @samp{X}
stands for a decimal number that will be incremented, if a so called
port already exists.

@item TOOLPRI
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{TOOLPRI}=@var{value}
@end format

This option allows you to change the priority of Scout's process
into @var{value}.

@item STARTUP
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{STARTUP}=@var{command}
@end format

The variable @var{command} should be an ARexx script or a single ARexx
command. Both (script or command) will be executed, when @code{Scout}
will be started. In this way you can open more than only the main
window by starting. Try for example the command @samp{OpenWindow Tasks}
and you will get two windows by starting (the main window and the
task list window).

(See also @ref{Commands, ARexx port, ARexx port}.)

@item INTERVALTIME
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{INTERVALTIME}=@var{seconds}
@end format

This options allows you to save your preferred update time for
the list of tasks.
(See also @ref{Tasks, Secs, Secs}.)

@item CPUDISPLAY
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{CPUDISPLAY}=@var{value}
@end format

Through the variable @var{value} you can select the state of the
@samp{CPU} cycle gadget you find in the @samp{Tasks} window.
(See also @ref{Tasks, CPU, CPU}.)

@itemize @bullet
@item @samp{1}  means  @samp{CPU: full}
@item @samp{2}  means  @samp{CPU: in %}
@end itemize

@item HOST
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{HOST}=@var{hostname}
@end format

This options allows you to specify the system (@var{hostname}) you
want to manipulate via network through @code{AmiTCP}.

@item USER
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{USER}=@var{username}
@end format

You have to use this option to identify yourself by using @code{Scout}
as a TCP/IP service.

@item PASSWORD
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{PASSWORD}=@var{password}
@end format

Without a password @code{Scout} can't connect to another system via
network. This option allows you to set the correct password.

@item COMMAND
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{COMMAND}=@var{commandline}
@end format

Nearly all of @code{Scout's} implemented functions are available from
shell through this option. You don't need the @samp{COMMAND} key to
use this option. (See also @ref{Commands}.)

@item SINGLEWINDOWS
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{SINGLEWINDOWS}
@end format

Some users don't like to handle the many windows of Scout. This option
solves the problem of too many windows. If this option is selected,
only one list window and only one detail window is opened at a time.

@end table


