@chapter Scout's commands via ARexx and shell
@cindex ARexx
@cindex Command

@noindent @code{Scout} supports two kinds of commands:

@enumerate
@item commands only available from shell
@item commands available from ARexx and shell
@end enumerate

@cindex ARexx port
@subheading ARexx port

It's a feature of @code{MUI} to give each application its own ARexx port.
Therefore @code{Scout} also has an ARexx port that usually has the
name @samp{SCOUT.X}. The @samp{X} stands for a decimal number that will be
incremented, if a so called port already exists.

You will find the name of @code{Scout's} ARexx port in the window you
get, if you select the @samp{Project/About} menu.

@cindex Tasknames
@subheading Using tasknames:

If a task or a process was started from shell and hasn't detached
itself, you will find the name of the command being executed, where
usually the taskname is displayed.  The real name of those tasks
usually is something like @samp{Background CLI}, but such a taskname
isn't useful.

@quotation
@strong{Example:} If you start a non detaching task like
@samp{DH0:Debug/Sushi} from shell, you will see @samp{DH0:Debug/Sushi}
as taskname.
@end quotation

Some ARexx commands need a taskname as parameter. You have to
select those from CLI started self detaching tasks by using their
command names like @code{Scout} displays them in the lists of tasks.

@section Commands only available from shell

@table @samp
@item Help
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{Help}
@end format

This command is the most important one and it doesn't need parameters.
If you try @code{Help}, @code{Scout} prints a list of all available
commands to shell.  =:^)
@end table

Now 18 commands follow. These commands allow the user to get all
lists of system structures from shell. Therefore you only need
to install @code{MUI} for using @code{Scout's} graphical user
interface.

Each of the following commands has a shortened form that stands behind
the command in parentheses.

@quotation
@code{Allocations} (a), @code{BoopsiClasses} (b),
@code{Commands} (c), @code{Devices} (d),
@code{Timer} (e), @code{Fonts} (f),
@code{Assigns} (g), @code{InputHandlers} (h),
@code{Interrupts} (i), @code{LowMemory} (j),
@code{Commodities} (k), @code{Libraries} (l),
@code{Memory} (m), @code{Mounts} (n),
@code{Locks} (o), @code{Ports} (p),
@code{Residents} (r), @code{Semaphores} (s),
@code{Tasks} (t), @code{Resources} (u),
@code{Vectors} (v), @code{Windows} (w),
@code{Expansions} (x), @code{System} (y) and
@code{ScreenMode} (z).
@end quotation

@quotation
@noindent @strong{Example:} To get the list of ports, you only have to
use @samp{scout ports} or @samp{scout p} from shell.
@end quotation

@section Commands available from ARexx and shell

@table @samp
@item FindTask
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{FindTask} @var{task}
@end format

This command allows you to check, if task @var{task} exists in
system or not. The result is the address of the task @var{task},
if it has been found. @var{task} can be the name or the address of
a task.

@item FreezeTask
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{FreezeTask} @var{task}
@end format

The task @var{taskname} will be frozen. After that it will still be
found in system's task list, but then it doesn't need processing time.
You can choose the name or the address of a task for @var{task}.

@item ActivateTask
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{ActivateTask} @var{task}
@end format

If task @var{task} was frozen, it will be activated, otherwise an
error occured. @var{task} is again a task's name or an address.

@item RemoveTask
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{RemoveTask} @var{task}
@end format

This command removes the task @var{task}. It's lost forever.

@item BreakTask
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{BreakTask} @var{task}
@end format

@code{Scout} sends the task @var{task} a certain signal mask
that includes the signals CTRL-C and CTRL-D. Many programs support
these signals and finish themselves, if they receive one of them.

@item SignalTask
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{SignalTask} @var{task} @var{hexsignal}
@end format

This command allows you to send a signal @var{hexsignal} to the task
@var{task}. The signal must specified as a hexadecimal number.

@strong{Example:}
@example
SendSignal 'scout' 0x001000
@end example
sends task @samp{scout} a CTRL-C and after that @code{Scout} ends.

@item SetTaskPri
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{SetTaskPri} @var{task} @var{priority}
@end format

The task @var{task} gets a new priority (@var{priority}).

@item RemovePort
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{RemovePort} @var{port}
@end format

The port @var{port} will be removed from @code{Scout}. @var{port}
can be the name of a port or its address.

@item GetLockNumber
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{GetLockNumber} @var{lockpattern}
@end format

This command returns the number of locks which have paths matching
to the pattern @var{lockpattern}.

@strong{Example:} Use the command
@example
GetLockNumber 'WORK:Utilities/#?'
@end example
and you will know, how many locks are currently used for files in the
directory @file{WORK:Utilities/}.

@item RemoveLocks
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{RemoveLocks} @var{lockpattern}
@end format

Use this command and all locks which have paths matching to the pattern
@var{lockpattern} will be removed.
(See also @code{GetLockNumber}.)

@item RemoveLock
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{RemoveLock} @var{lockaddress}
@end format

The lock at adress @var{lockaddress} will be removed.

@item FindNode
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{FindNode} @var{nodetype} @var{nodename}
@end format

This command allows you to find a certain node. You only have
to know its name (@var{nodename}) and its type (@var{nodetype}).

@var{Nodetype} can have following values:  @samp{LIBRARY},
@samp{DEVICE}, @samp{RESOURCE}, @samp{MEMORY}, @samp{SEMAPHORE},
@samp{PORT} or @samp{INPUTHANDLER}.

@strong{Example:} If you want to get the address of the
@samp{disk.resource} you must use:
@example
FindNode RESOURCE 'disk.resource'
@end example

@item GetPriority
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{GetPriority} @var{nodeaddress}
@end format

This command allows you to check the priority of a certain node
structure. This includes all following structure types:  tasks,
libraries, devices, resources, ports, residents, input handlers,
interrupts, semaphores and the elements of the memory list.

You only have to know the address (@var{nodeaddress}) of that
structure.

@strong{Example:} The following ARexx commands store the priority of
your chip memory in the variable @samp{pri}:
@example
FindName MEMORY 'chip memory'
addr = result
GetPriority addr
pri = result
@end example

@item SetPriority
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{SetPriority} @var{nodetype} @var{nodename}
@end format

If you want to change the priority of the node @var{nodename}, you can
use this command.  Again @var{nodetype} can have following values:
@samp{LIBRARY}, @samp{DEVICE}, @samp{RESOURCE}, @samp{MEMORY},
@samp{SEMAPHORE}, @samp{PORT} or @samp{INPUTHANDLER}.

@item CloseLibrary
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{CloseLibrary} @var{library}
@end format

The library @var{library} will be closed once. @var{library} can be
the name of the library or its address.

@item RemoveLibrary
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{RemoveLibrary} @var{library}
@end format

The library @var{library} will be removed, if no program uses it.

@item RemoveDevice
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{RemoveDevice} @var{device}
@end format

The selected device @var{device} will be removed. For @var{device}
use the name or the address of the device.

@item RemoveResource
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{RemoveResource} @var{resource}
@end format

The resource @var{resource} will be removed.

@item ObtainSemaphore
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{ObtainSemaphore} @var{semaphore}
@end format

This command allows you to obtain the given semaphore. @var{semaphore}
can be the semaphore's name or address.

@item ReleaseSemaphore
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{ReleaseSemaphore} @var{semaphore}
@end format

The semaphore @var{semaphore} will be once released.

@item RemoveSemaphore
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{RemoveSemaphore} @var{semaphore}
@end format

You are able to remove the semaphore @var{semaphore} by using this
command.

@item RemoveInputhandler
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{RemoveInputhandler} @var{inputhandler}
@end format

The input handler @var{inputhandler} selected through name or address
will be removed.

@item FindResident
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{FindResident} @var{resident}
@end format

This command returns the address of the resident structure
@var{resident}.

@item FindInterrupt
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{FindInterrupt} @var{interruptname}
@end format

The address of the interrupt @var{interruptname} will be returned.

@item RemoveInterrupt
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{RemoveInterrupt} @var{interruptname}
@end format

The interrupt you have selected through @var{interruptname} will be
removed.

@item FlushDevs
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{FlushDevs}
@end format

All not used devices will be removed. The used memory will be freed.

@item FlushFonts
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{FlushFonts}
@end format

If a diskfont is in memory, but no program uses it, it will be
removed.

@item FlushLibs
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{FlushLibs}
@end format

All not used libraries will be removed. The used memory will be freed.

@item FlushAll
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{FlushAll}
@end format

This function includes @code{FlushDevs}, @code{FlushFonts} and
@code{FlushLibs}. All not used devices, libraries and fonts
will be removed and the used memory will be freed.

@item ClearResetVectors
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{ClearResetVectors}
@end format

The six reset vectors will be cleared, if you select this function
(see @ref{Vectors}).

@item PopToFront
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{PopToFront} @var{title}
@end format

This command allows you to pop a screen or window to front. You
only have to know its (@var{title}).

@item CloseWindow
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{CloseWindow} @var{windowtitle}
@end format

This command closes the window that is specified through its title
(@var{windowtitle}).

@item CloseScreen
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{CloseScreen} @var{screentitle}
@end format

If you select this command, the screen (@var{screentitle}) will be
closed with all its windows.

@item CloseFont
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{CloseFont} @var{address}
@end format

The font at address @var{address} will be closed once.

@item RemoveFont
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{RemoveFont} @var{address}
@end format

This command removes the font at address @var{address}, if it's
not used by any program.

@item RemoveCommand
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{RemoveCommand} @var{address}
@end format

@code{Scout} makes the resident command at address @var{address}
not resident.

@item RemoveAssign
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{RemoveAssign} @var{name}
@end format

With this command you're able to remove the assign @var{name}.

@item RemoveAssignList
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{RemoveAssignList} @var{name} @var{address}
@end format

This command removes the directory at address @var{address} from
assign @var{name}. You will find the address of that directory in
the list of assigns.

@item PrintList
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{PrintList} @var{listcharacter} @var{filename}
@end format

This command allows you to print a list (specified by the
listcharacter) into the file @var{filename}.

@strong{Example:}
@example
PrintList t 'ram:tasklist'
@end example
will print the list of tasks into the file 'ram:tasklist'.

@item OpenWindow
@format
@strong{Usage:} @code{OpenWindow} @var{windowid}
@end format

All windows you get if you select a gadget of @code{Scout's} main window,
can be opened with this command.  The @var{windowid} is the same text you
find on the main window gadgets.

@strong{Example:}
@example
OpenWindow 'Mounted Devs'
@end example
will open the window with the list of mounted devices.

@item CxAppear
@itemx CxDisappear
@itemx CxEnable
@itemx CxDisable
@itemx CxKill
@itemx CxListChg
@itemx CxUnique
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{Cx...} @var{name}
@end format

Sends the command to the commodity named @var{name}.

@item RemoveCx
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{RemoveCx} @var{commodity}
@end format

Removes the appropriate commodity from the list. Please consider this as
`emergency break'. Use it only if @code{CxKill} failed.

@item SetCxPri
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{SetCxPri} @var{commodity} @var{priority}
@end format

Sets the priority of a commodity.

@item RemoveClass
@format
@strong{Format:} @code{RemoveClass} @var{class}
@end format

The appropriate BOOPSI class is removed, if no objects and no subclasses
are existing.


@end table


